rcarragher:
I'd like to reuse the injector from one run to the next. This is going to mean that I need access to the injectors instance variable. I've been goofing with this locally, and it has made a significant performance improvement for us. The idea is, if we don't yet have an injector (i.e. this is the first test run), let RoboGuice do it's thing. Otherwise, reuse the injector. Now, in our prepareTest(), instead of using RoboGuice.setBaseApplicationInjector(), we use TestRoboGuice.getTestInjector().
```
public class TestRoboGuice extends RoboGuice {
    public TestRoboGuice(){}
private static Injector injector = null;

public static Injector getTestInjector(final Application application, Stage stage, Module... modules){
    if (injector == null){
        injector = setBaseApplicationInjector(application,stage,modules);
    } else {
        injectors.put(application,injector);
    }
    return injector;
}

}
``
. Because the injectors map in RoboGuice is declared protected, by inheriting from RoboGuice I can have access to it. In other words, sub-classing gives me direct access to what I need, note theinjectors.put()` in my snippet above. In order to test this, I forked RoboGuice and removed final from the class definition, and it worked very well.
That said, I'm open to another way to solve this. Let me know how I can help.
