jon-adams:
I can confirm the official Android support library Nullable does cause this problem.
In the short term, the wiki https://github.com/roboguice/roboguice/wiki/What%27s-the-difference-between-Nullable-and-Optional%3F should be updated to reflect this. Right now it still advises users that the support library will work, which it does not.
In the long term, RoboGuice should either implement its own, or depend on a simple library that has a standard implementation that has an appropriate retention policy.
Also, the error log message in this case should mention the retention policything, since users might continue to use the Nullable from the support library not knowing that it won't work. It will greatly confused them if they see a Nullable in the source but then see a error message saying its not.
Workaround: You can use most other Nullable annotation instances, or even write your own easily, since RoboGuice only checks for the class name by string compare to "Nullable".
I am currently using the Findbugs implementation of the official JSR for Nullable. To use that, in your module gradle.build add:
compile 'com.google.code.findbugs:jsr305:1.3.9'
. RoboGuice 3.0 did indeed change RoboActivity.shouldInjectOnCreateView to always return false to "fix" this. However, then you don't get view injection in some cases. 
I prefer to instead replace RoboActivity with the same one as RoboGuice 3 except I leave the RoboGuice 2 shouldInjectOnCreateView method the way it was. To get around the original crash though, I add additional filters as I come across them. Example:
```
protected static boolean shouldInjectOnCreateView(final String name) {
     // RoboGuice 3 implementation
     // return false; // boo! lazy fix
 // original RoboGuice 2 implementation
 return Character.isLowerCase(name.charAt(0)) && !name.startsWith("com.android") 
        && !name.equals("fragment")
        // this is an additional namespace I've added to this logic filter
        && !name.startsWith("android.widget");

}
```
.

